so I'll go into talking about things that actually happened

21
00:02:17,678 --> 00:02:21,220
and what we decided to do at those instances.

22
00:02:21,220 --> 00:02:24,401
I think that'll make things easier to understand.

23
00:02:30,748 --> 00:02:32,470
and you'll get much more useful information out of it.

24
00:02:32,470 --> 00:02:33,870
So we'll talk about actual concerns, problems, issues,

25
00:02:33,870 --> 00:02:34,971
and challenges that we face with these titles.

26
00:02:34,971 --> 00:02:35,792
Let's first talk about RuneFactory.

27
00:03:01,511 --> 00:03:05,153
The concept of this game is living the fantasy life.

28
00:03:05,153 --> 00:03:11,135
The main theme isn't necessarily about the often used premise of

29
00:03:11,135 --> 00:03:11,975
adventure.

30
00:03:11,975 --> 00:03:14,876
It's about living a relaxed life in a fantasy world, and

31
00:03:14,876 --> 00:03:15,977
eventually passing away.

32
00:03:15,977 --> 00:03:18,198
I wanted to make a game rooted in such a premise.

33
00:03:30,466 --> 00:03:32,507
In JRPGs, you see a lot of settings where the main

34
00:03:32,507 --> 00:03:33,487
character is a hero and as someone special or of some

35
00:03:33,487 --> 00:03:34,908
status. But I wanted to make a game where you as a main

36
00:03:34,908 --> 00:03:36,308
character may not necessarily be a hero, but you still live a

37
00:03:36,308 --> 00:03:36,729
very rich life.

38
00:03:56,032 --> 00:03:59,393
For example, in the very beginning of Lord of the Rings,

39
00:03:59,393 --> 00:04:00,994
there's the Hobbit village.

40
00:04:00,994 --> 00:04:03,516
The game is similar to that, but you don't find the ring

41
00:04:03,516 --> 00:04:04,836
and instead live a very peaceful, long life.

42
00:04:04,836 --> 00:04:05,837
I also wanted to make a gameplay system

43
00:04:05,837 --> 00:04:07,878
that is different from RPGs that has come before it.

44
00:04:24,952 --> 00:04:30,856
We did our best to avoid having the villagers repeat the same message over and over.

45
00:04:30,856 --> 00:04:34,118
And instead of just being simple NPCs,

46
00:04:34,118 --> 00:04:36,720
they act like main characters and act under their own AI.

47
00:04:36,720 --> 00:04:39,742
Everyone in the village, even the old men and the women,

48
00:04:39,742 --> 00:04:40,883
they have their stories to tell.

49
00:04:54,807 --> 00:04:55,888
and they have their own existence.

50
00:04:55,888 --> 00:04:57,049
They have their own opinions and concerns, just like any other person.

51
00:04:57,049 --> 00:04:59,430
Getting into a battle doesn't mean you'll come away with gold and treasures.

52
00:04:59,430 --> 00:05:01,792
The main character has to work very, very hard, raise crops to earn a livelihood in

53
00:05:01,792 --> 00:05:02,432
order to exist.

54
00:05:23,782 --> 00:05:29,186
It's more like a game that features the realistic side of things that most tend to ignore in the fantasy worlds and settings.

55
00:05:29,186 --> 00:05:31,028
When you step outside the village, there are dungeons about.

56
00:05:31,028 --> 00:05:31,628
These dungeons have bosses.

57
00:05:31,628 --> 00:05:32,229
And once you leave for an adventure.

58
00:05:51,506 --> 00:05:54,609
The road is very, very long and pearls about.

59
00:05:54,609 --> 00:05:55,890
Then I thought about the concept of water stations during a real

60
00:05:55,890 --> 00:05:57,091
life marathon as if it was a similar long, long road.

61
00:05:57,091 --> 00:06:01,354
If you take breaks during your dungeon crawl, just like at the

62
00:06:01,354 --> 00:06:06,038
water station, I felt that people would be able to overcome

63
00:06:06,038 --> 00:06:07,419
them without giving up.

64
00:06:23,651 --> 00:06:26,634
But to capitalize on the game systems,

65
00:06:26,634 --> 00:06:28,635
we also put fields in the middle

66
00:06:28,635 --> 00:06:30,257
so that you can raise crops to revitalize yourself,

67
00:06:30,257 --> 00:06:32,479
give yourself more energy.

68
00:06:32,479 --> 00:06:33,820
And this happened to work out in the end.

69
00:06:33,820 --> 00:06:34,360
People who are good at the game

70
00:06:34,360 --> 00:06:37,002
do not need to rest and cultivate crops.

71
00:06:37,002 --> 00:06:38,083
While people who feel that the game is hard,

72
00:06:51,309 --> 00:06:55,093
can do so that the game design adapts to the player's play style.

73
00:06:55,093 --> 00:06:57,395
Then in the summertime, the characters change into swimwear.

74
00:07:18,022 --> 00:07:24,684
When this happens, female characters sometimes put on a tattoo-like symbol on their bodies.

75
00:07:24,684 --> 00:07:27,005
This is actually a form of sunblock in this particular fantasy world.

76
00:07:27,005 --> 00:07:30,006
At the time, because of the way we built the characters, we couldn't make them tan, and

77
00:07:30,006 --> 00:07:30,826
we were looking for a way to get around this.

78
00:07:46,848 --> 00:07:50,090
We also figured that even in this fantasy world, there would be girls who would like to tan and those who wouldn't.

79
00:07:50,090 --> 00:07:56,133
From there, we embraced the idea that in this fantasy world, people didn't use sunblock as we do in real life, but instead put on tattoos to avoid the sun.

80
00:08:14,938 --> 00:08:16,360
It was a way to take something realistic and put a fantasy spin on it.

81
00:08:16,360 --> 00:08:17,621
Also in terms of outfits, because it's about people who work in the fields,

82
00:08:17,621 --> 00:08:18,682
a lot of us would assume that they wouldn't care much about their

83
00:08:18,682 --> 00:08:19,382
appearance and what they're wearing.

84
00:08:37,672 --> 00:08:39,953
But we figured that because everyone is doing the same day in and day out,

85
00:08:39,953 --> 00:08:42,915
that they wanted to do something to stand out and maybe be noticed.

86
00:08:42,915 --> 00:08:44,475
When we went out to the real farms and asked young farmers,

87
00:08:44,475 --> 00:08:45,436
they actually felt the same way.

88
00:08:45,436 --> 00:08:46,396
So we decided to implement this idea.

89
00:09:10,571 --> 00:09:12,412
As such, when you put in little bits of realism from real life, it helps resonate with the

90
00:09:12,412 --> 00:09:17,595
players and makes it much easier to feel as though if it were real.

91
00:09:17,595 --> 00:09:23,578
Even if you have a great idea, a unique idea, if your users don't understand it, what is

92
00:09:23,578 --> 00:09:25,119
the point, right?

93
00:09:41,190 --> 00:09:46,154
They're certainly not going to think it's fun unless they really understand what you're

94
00:09:46,154 --> 00:09:46,635
trying to communicate.

95
00:09:46,635 --> 00:09:47,496
It's the same thing with movies.

96
00:09:52,603 --> 00:09:56,386
After you finish watching a movie and walk out of the theater, you sometimes feel as

97
00:09:56,386 --> 00:09:59,869
though you could do what you just saw.

98
00:09:59,869 --> 00:10:04,833
For instance, if you saw a superhero movie, you feel like you've become powerful.

99
00:10:04,833 --> 00:10:10,978
And if you see a movie about magic, you almost feel as though you could actually cast magic,

100
00:10:10,978 --> 00:10:12,539
but you just didn't realize it until now.

101
00:10:15,466 --> 00:10:18,169
This, I think, is proof that bits of realism from real life

102
00:10:18,169 --> 00:10:20,291
is connecting with the audience.

103
00:10:20,291 --> 00:10:22,674
I want to make a game where we don't just lean on the

104
00:10:22,674 --> 00:10:27,460
fantastical and instead make it feel somehow real and relatable.

105
00:10:38,264 --> 00:10:45,187
With games, we have an advantage over movies in that players can also do what they want to do.

106
00:10:45,187 --> 00:10:48,488
They can choose their route, the way they want to live.

107
00:10:48,488 --> 00:10:52,430
For example, in Room Factory, when you become friends with the girl, you can get married and even have a baby.

108
00:10:52,430 --> 00:10:53,831
In the latest version, you can even play as a girl.

109
00:10:53,831 --> 00:10:56,212
And when they become friends with the boy, they can get married and have a baby together.

110
00:11:12,832 --> 00:11:13,692
How far can we go in living our life in this game?

111
00:11:13,692 --> 00:11:14,753
If you want to simply live together with your partner, you can.

112
00:11:14,753 --> 00:11:15,995
And if you want to go defeat the demon together, you can also do that.

113
00:11:15,995 --> 00:11:17,296
We wanted to make a game where people felt like they didn't want the world to end.

114
00:11:38,910 --> 00:11:40,230
as if they didn't want to clear it because then that world would be over.

115
00:11:40,230 --> 00:11:41,090
Next, I'm going to talk about Muramasa, the Demon Blade.

116
00:11:41,090 --> 00:11:42,211
As you may know, this is a Japanese themed swordplay action RPG.

117
00:11:42,211 --> 00:11:42,731
The motif is very Japanese.

118
00:11:42,731 --> 00:11:43,231
There are 108 swords in the game.

119
00:12:09,888 --> 00:12:11,809
This number of swords is significant, as the number of 108 is known as the number of earthly

120
00:12:11,809 --> 00:12:17,291
desires human beings are born with in Japan.

121
00:12:17,291 --> 00:12:25,114
Also, the oni characters that appear in the game were created to be different from ogres

122
00:12:25,114 --> 00:12:26,435
that originate in the West.

123
00:12:40,824 --> 00:12:44,867
I often see oni translated as ogres, but I like to treat oni

124
00:12:44,867 --> 00:12:46,868
as oni and design them as such.

125
00:12:46,868 --> 00:12:49,709
As for the characters that appear in Muramasa, there are

126
00:12:49,709 --> 00:12:51,210
some Japanese, there are some characters that Japanese people

127
00:12:51,210 --> 00:12:51,431
recognize.

128
00:13:09,708 --> 00:13:11,029
In the Japanese version, the conversations were written in

129
00:13:11,029 --> 00:13:12,229
such a way that it would be slightly difficult to

130
00:13:12,229 --> 00:13:13,530
understand, even for a Japanese person.

131
00:13:13,530 --> 00:13:14,691
Let me just give you a quick example.

132
00:13:14,691 --> 00:13:16,172
The girl, Momohime, is the princess, and the boy, Onisuke,

133
00:13:16,172 --> 00:13:16,852
Kisuke, are the main characters.

134
00:13:40,717 --> 00:13:43,699
Momohime is a princess and speaks like royalty, and Kisuke is a ninja, so he speaks with a

135
00:13:43,699 --> 00:13:44,439
thrilling Edoko-style dialect.

136
00:13:44,439 --> 00:13:47,681
In addition, in the case of Momohime, she'll take on other souls, which also cause her

137
00:13:47,681 --> 00:13:48,482
to switch up the way she speaks.

138
00:13:48,482 --> 00:13:50,503
So even if the situation presented in front of them is the same between these characters,

139
00:14:08,948 --> 00:14:10,990
Depending on which role they play, we change up the way they talk and the way they grow.

140
00:14:10,990 --> 00:14:12,631
Also in the game, there are lots of edible things and items that appear along the way.

141
00:14:12,631 --> 00:14:13,952
It's said that all foods contain life energy called Seiki.

142
00:14:38,473 --> 00:14:40,694
And foods that are special even have a soul.

143
00:14:40,694 --> 00:14:41,755
By eating the food, the main characters gain its strength from

144
00:14:41,755 --> 00:14:44,297
Seiki and uses that strength to increase the power of their

145
00:14:44,297 --> 00:14:44,758
blades.

146
00:14:44,758 --> 00:14:50,802
In terms of the setting, it takes place during the Genroku

147
00:14:50,802 --> 00:14:53,765
era, which encompasses the Edo period.

148
00:15:07,657 --> 00:15:09,458
It covers the latter years of the 17th century and into the

149
00:15:09,458 --> 00:15:09,498
18th.

150
00:15:09,498 --> 00:15:11,559
At the time, fatty tuna, or as we know it here, toro, was not

151
00:15:11,559 --> 00:15:12,960
valued like it is now. The less fatty red meat was actually more

152
00:15:12,960 --> 00:15:13,120
valuable.

153
00:15:38,575 --> 00:15:41,036
and maguro sushi, the tuna sushi, was not very expensive at all.

154
00:15:41,036 --> 00:15:42,417
At the time, they also started farming sea bream and flounder.

155
00:15:42,417 --> 00:15:43,477
So while the prices were high, they could buy them.

156
00:16:08,383 --> 00:16:09,784
We wanted to show a food world that is different from what we know today.

157
00:16:09,784 --> 00:16:10,624
But of course, this world did not actually exist.

158
00:16:10,624 --> 00:16:11,525
This is still a Japanese-styled fantasy world.

159
00:16:11,525 --> 00:16:13,826
Just like in Rune Factory, however, by injecting some realistic elements into the world,

160
00:16:36,142 --> 00:16:39,824
it made it much easier to play and believe.

161
00:16:39,824 --> 00:16:46,386
Also, we made it so that you can change characters at any time,

162
00:16:46,386 --> 00:16:49,928
as well as change difficulties at will.

163
00:16:49,928 --> 00:16:52,309
We wanted players to be able to pick their own route

164
00:16:52,309 --> 00:16:54,870
and play the way they want.

165
00:16:54,870 --> 00:16:58,131
Having player choice is what makes games

166
00:16:58,131 --> 00:16:59,771
different from other mediums.

167
00:17:06,223 --> 00:17:10,786
So I'm going to talk a little bit about the emphasis on action, even though we're talking

168
00:17:10,786 --> 00:17:11,567
about RPGs.

169
00:17:11,567 --> 00:17:18,611
I often make RPGs and simulation games, but I feel that there needs to be an emphasis

170
00:17:18,611 --> 00:17:21,152
on action within these games.

171
00:17:21,152 --> 00:17:27,676
Because they're meant to be games that you play for a very long time, you almost have

172
00:17:27,676 --> 00:17:32,018
to have controls that feel even better than actual action games.

173
00:17:35,879 --> 00:17:37,581
For example, let's say if it takes a very, very long time

174
00:17:37,581 --> 00:17:40,263
to close a window to the point you get irritated.

175
00:17:40,263 --> 00:17:42,065
And then on top of that, whenever that window closes,

176
00:17:42,065 --> 00:17:42,946
it makes a weird system noise.

177
00:17:42,946 --> 00:17:45,548
You would think that as you play, you'll get used to it.

178
00:18:05,499 --> 00:18:21,965
But in reality, the stress actually begins to build until it gets to a point where players may actually stop playing, or they may just end up hating the game altogether, even though they actually like the game, the inside of the game.

179
00:18:21,965 --> 00:18:23,065
Not everyone who plays games is a hardcore fan.

180
00:18:36,161 --> 00:18:37,582
This may not apply to a lot of you here today, but it is true.

181
00:18:37,582 --> 00:18:40,024
And so, because of this, you really have to emphasize good action.

182
00:18:40,024 --> 00:18:41,265
But I think for me, perhaps this comes from my roots.

183
00:19:06,614 --> 00:19:07,695
I've worked on many action games and fighting games in the past.

184
00:19:07,695 --> 00:19:09,235
And to just give you an example, when you have a character jump, you don't just repeat

185
00:19:09,235 --> 00:19:09,735
the same up and down movements.

186
00:19:09,735 --> 00:19:10,616
You need to have acceleration to feel it.

187
00:19:10,616 --> 00:19:10,896
Or when you punch.

188
00:19:30,465 --> 00:19:34,047
You get the punch to feel good by having the punch come out

189
00:19:34,047 --> 00:19:37,550
very, very quickly, followed by a slower reset.

190
00:19:37,550 --> 00:19:38,771
I learned a lot of this through trial and error.

191
00:19:38,771 --> 00:19:40,892
I think this kind of tuning in relation to timing

192
00:19:40,892 --> 00:19:41,993
is something that I still value.

193
00:20:02,533 --> 00:20:06,655
So now I'm going to talk a little bit about the volume

194
00:20:06,655 --> 00:20:11,438
and flow of information using a specific example

195
00:20:11,438 --> 00:20:12,138
that you see here.

196
00:20:20,688 --> 00:20:23,670
When making a game, the creator must control the amount of

197
00:20:23,670 --> 00:20:27,672
information along with the course of development or

198
00:20:27,672 --> 00:20:31,434
progress of the game. In my early days when I was designing

199
00:20:31,434 --> 00:20:33,035
a stage in an arcade game, I thought of this gimmick. The

200
00:20:33,035 --> 00:20:35,477
ground splits halfway through, as you can see, and beneath it

201
00:20:35,477 --> 00:20:36,037
lays a pool of magma.

202
00:20:49,636 --> 00:20:50,897
If you proceed straight, the path is a dead end,

203
00:20:50,897 --> 00:20:51,457
and there's a switch.

204
00:20:51,457 --> 00:20:52,858
By explaining the elements in this fashion

205
00:20:52,858 --> 00:20:53,519
and not overthinking it, one may wonder,

206
00:20:53,519 --> 00:20:54,500
something's going to happen if I put on the switch, right?

207
00:20:54,500 --> 00:20:55,220
But when we actually did a focus group,

208
00:20:55,220 --> 00:20:56,161
the reaction confirmed that it was wishful thinking.

209
00:21:18,475 --> 00:21:20,176
I thought for sure the players would turn on the switch, but I was wrong.

210
00:21:20,176 --> 00:21:22,177
Instead they plunged right into the magma.

211
00:21:22,177 --> 00:21:23,758
That's an instant game over, and many felt it was pretty unreasonable.

212
00:21:23,758 --> 00:21:26,720
So instead of instantly dying, we adjusted it so you would gradually lose health.

213
00:21:44,986 --> 00:21:46,447
but that actually didn't do much either.

214
00:21:46,447 --> 00:21:47,388
In fact, they would run into the magma even more

215
00:21:47,388 --> 00:21:49,569
and would die one after another.

216
00:21:49,569 --> 00:21:50,710
In this case, in addition to not being able

217
00:21:50,710 --> 00:21:51,310
to understand what to do,

218
00:21:51,310 --> 00:21:53,032
there was simply just too much going on.

219
00:21:53,032 --> 00:21:53,912
We were asking for more decisions to be made

220
00:21:53,912 --> 00:21:54,233
than one can handle.

221
00:22:12,086 --> 00:22:18,589
So there was a dead end, there was a switch, the enemies were approaching, and then you

222
00:22:18,589 --> 00:22:18,809
had magma.

223
00:22:18,809 --> 00:22:20,450
These conditions made it very difficult to figure out what your next move was going to

224
00:22:20,450 --> 00:22:20,490
be.

225
00:22:20,490 --> 00:22:22,811
By adjusting the condition of magma from instant death to loss of health, it's possible to

226
00:22:22,811 --> 00:22:24,812
say that the players briefly forgot about what to do with the switch and ran right into

227
00:22:24,812 --> 00:22:25,192
the magma instead.

228
00:22:42,255 --> 00:22:45,698
In the end, we didn't want to scratch the idea, so we added the word

229
00:22:45,698 --> 00:22:49,701
pool to the switch and assigned that command to the controller stick

230
00:22:49,701 --> 00:22:54,265
as if you were actually pulling. There may have been other ways to solve this,

231
00:22:54,265 --> 00:22:57,868
but when the players finally understood it, I learned two things.

232
00:22:57,868 --> 00:23:02,191
How challenging it is to communicate your intentions to the player,

233
00:23:02,191 --> 00:23:05,734
and the relief and joy when you succeed at doing just that.

234
00:23:11,817 --> 00:23:15,180
In RPGs, there are various missions and side quests.

235
00:23:15,180 --> 00:23:16,201
In a way, this is a result of needing

